rComments: A bit stubborn, inconsistent feedback, doesnt speak clearly, awesome guest speakers, readings arent applicable, wants to help but struggles as he is not an academic, sometimes fun activities, good guy!

Prof. Cox is a lovely old man with a wealth of experience but that seems to be it. He started off every lecture with the exact same spiel (20 mins). He appeared to be poorly trained for example he did not know the difference between research and analytical methods. Terrible feedback, he says one thing and the next time says the other.
Has so much life experience to share with us in the course material. Lectures can be dry, but had great guest speakers and is a very genuine professor.

He expects a lot from his students, but has the knowledge and expertise to back it up. His lectures are sometimes dry, but if you are interested in foreign policy it is very interesting to hear from someone who helped implement it. Great guest speakers, and overall a very interesting and rewarding class, if you can wrap your head around the theory.

He's a real hard-***. He's not specific and you have to guess what he wants on your papers or in your exams. The class is ok itself, we didn't learn that much (you can easily look up the case studies yourself). Great guest speakers thought.

Worst prof of my degree. He has no interest in hearing anything but a reverberation of his opinion. Papers need to be exactly what he wants but he makes you guess what that is. Great guest speakers but they have zero bearing on evaluations or real connection to course material. Don't bother taking notes - they don't help you during exams.

Interesting course with professor Cox. Contained a number of guest speakers that were quite interesting in their own right but didn't necessarily relate directly to the exams. He would also criticize the textbook endlessly, but still expect the class to know tons of very specific information from it. Helpful one-on-one but not so much in the class.
